{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848603110,"sessionID":"ses_2872d2701ffev3BAEK1ktxyhTW","part":{"id":"prt_d78d33dbe001KnYN04DgXx88I8","messageID":"msg_d78d2e24a001UrYGl6E2hInlAP","sessionID":"ses_2872d2701ffev3BAEK1ktxyhTW","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-b3afab367a1c4510995ef05bff65935e","state":{"status":"error","input":{"content":"# AR-009: Router HTTP Reverse Proxy Core\n\n## Module\n`pkg/router`\n\n## Language\nGo\n\n## Size\nM\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nImplement a high-performance HTTP reverse proxy core for the AgentCube runtime that serves as the entry point for incoming agent requests. The router will:\n\n1. Accept and route HTTP requests to appropriate agent backends based on routing rules\n2. Manage connection pooling and keep-alive for efficient resource utilization\n3. Provide load balancing capabilities across multiple agent instances\n4. Integrate with Kubernetes API for dynamic backend discovery via `AgentRuntime` and `CodeInterpreter` resources\n5. Support middleware for authentication, rate limiting, request/response transformation\n6. Enable observability through metrics, logging, and tracing\n\n## Scope\n\n### Core Components\n\n1. **Router Engine**\n   - HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2 support\n   - Request routing logic based on path, headers, and query parameters\n   - Backend selection strategy (round-robin, least-connections, IP hash)\n   - Health check integration with Kubernetes readiness probes\n\n2. **Backend Management**\n   - Dynamic backend discovery using client-go informers\n   - Watch `AgentRuntime` and `CodeInterpreter` resources for updates\n   - Maintain backend pool state and service endpoints\n   - Handle backend health status and automatic failover\n\n3. **Middleware Framework**\n   - Pluggable middleware chain architecture\n   - Built-in middleware: authentication, rate limiting, CORS, request logging\n   - Custom middleware support via interface\n\n4. **Observability**\n   - Prometheus metrics (request count, latency, error rate, backend health)\n   - Structured logging with request IDs\n   - Distributed tracing support (OpenTelemetry)\n\n5. **Configuration**\n   - Configurable routing rules via Kubernetes ConfigMap or CRD\n   - Hot-reload support for configuration changes\n   - TLS termination and certificate management\n\n### Integration Points\n\n- **Kubernetes API**: Use generated client-go library for backend discovery\n  - `AgentRuntimeInterface` for agent runtime resources\n  - `CodeInterpreterInterface` for code interpreter resources\n  - Informers for real-time updates\n- **Agent Manager**: Communicate with agent manager for backend health checks\n- **Monitoring System**: Export metrics to Prometheus/Grafana\n- **Certificate Manager**: Integration for TLS certificate lifecycle\n\n### Out of Scope\n\n- WebSocket support (deferred to future iteration)\n- gRPC reverse proxy (deferred to future iteration)\n- Advanced routing features like canary deployments, A/B testing\n- Custom protocol handlers beyond HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Dependencies\n\n1. **New Dependencies**\n   - `github.com/gorilla/mux` or `github.com/gin-gonic/gin` for HTTP routing\n   - `github.com/prometheus/client_golang` for metrics export\n   - `go.opentelemetry.io/otel` for distributed tracing\n   - Existing client-go library for Kubernetes API integration\n\n2. **Module Dependencies**\n   - `pkg/agent`: Backend health check integration\n   - `pkg/config`: Configuration management\n   - `pkg/metrics`: Metrics collection and export\n   - `pkg/logger`: Structured logging\n\n### Architectural Changes\n\n1. **New Package Structure**\n   ```\n   pkg/router/\n   ├── engine.go           # HTTP router engine\n   ├── backend.go          # Backend pool management\n   ├── middleware.go       # Middleware framework\n   ├── routing.go          # Routing logic and rules\n   ├── informer.go         # Kubernetes informer integration\n   ├── health.go           # Health checks\n   ├── metrics.go          # Metrics collection\n   └── config.go           # Configuration handling\n   ```\n\n2. **Service Architecture**\n   - Router runs as a separate deployment in Kubernetes\n   - Exposes service via Kubernetes Service (LoadBalancer/NodePort)\n   - Uses informers for dynamic backend discovery\n   - No shared state between router instances (stateless design)\n\n3. **API Changes**\n   - No changes to existing CRDs\n   - Potential new CRD for routing rules (RoutingPolicy)\n\n### Performance Considerations\n\n1. **Target Performance Metrics**\n   - Request throughput: >10,000 RPS per instance\n   - P99 latency: <50ms for proxying to healthy backends\n   - Memory footprint: <200MB per instance\n   - CPU usage: <2 cores at peak load\n\n2. **Resource Requirements**\n   - Horizontal scaling: Multiple router instances behind a load balancer\n   - Backend connection pooling: Reuse connections for efficiency\n   - Cache frequently accessed routing rules\n\n### Security Considerations\n\n1. **Authentication & Authorization**\n   - JWT token validation middleware\n   - Integration with Kubernetes service account tokens\n   - Request-level access control based on routing rules\n\n2. **TLS Configuration**\n   - TLS termination at router\n   - Certificate rotation via cert-manager\n   - Support for mutual TLS (mTLS) for backend communication\n\n3. **Rate Limiting**\n   - Per-IP rate limiting to prevent abuse\n   - Per-backend rate limiting for protection\n   - Configurable limits via routing policy\n\n### Testing Strategy\n\n1. **Unit Tests**\n   - Router logic and rule matching\n   - Backend pool management\n   - Middleware chain execution\n   - Kubernetes informer integration (using fake clients)\n\n2. **Integration Tests**\n   - End-to-end proxying with mock backends\n   - Kubernetes informer updates triggering backend changes\n   - Metrics export verification\n   - TLS termination tests\n\n3. **Performance Tests**\n   - Load testing with realistic request patterns\n   - Memory leak detection\n   - Concurrent request handling\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Alternative 1: Use Existing Ingress Controller\n\n**Approach**: Leverage Kubernetes Ingress controllers (NGINX, Traefik) for routing.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Battle-tested and well-documented\n- Rich ecosystem of plugins and integrations\n- No custom development required\n\n**Cons**:\n- Limited control over custom routing logic\n- Tighter coupling to Kubernetes ingress API\n- May not meet specific AgentCube routing requirements\n- Additional complexity in configuration management\n\n**Decision**: Build custom router for greater flexibility and better alignment with AgentCube-specific requirements.\n\n### Alternative 2: Service Mesh (Istio/Linkerd)\n\n**Approach**: Implement routing via service mesh sidecars.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Advanced traffic management features\n- Built-in observability and security\n- Canary deployments and A/B testing support\n\n**Cons**:\n- Significant infrastructure overhead\n- Steep learning curve for operations team\n- Overkill for initial requirements\n- Increased resource consumption (sidecars per pod)\n\n**Decision**: Postpone service mesh adoption until advanced routing features are needed.\n\n### Alternative 3: gRPC Reverse Proxy\n\n**Approach**: Use gRPC reverse proxy for agent communication.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Efficient binary protocol\n- Built-in load balancing and retries\n- Strongly typed service definitions\n\n**Cons**:\n- Limited HTTP support (gRPC-web required)\n- Smaller ecosystem compared to HTTP\n- Not aligned with current agent API design\n\n**Decision**: Stick with HTTP for now, consider gRPC in future iterations if requirements evolve.\n\n## Timeline\n\n### Phase 1: Core Router (Weeks 1-4)\n- Basic HTTP routing engine\n- Backend pool management\n- Kubernetes informer integration\n- Health checks\n\n### Phase 2: Middleware & Security (Weeks 5-6)\n- Middleware framework\n- Authentication middleware\n- TLS termination\n- Rate limiting\n\n### Phase 3: Observability & Configuration (Weeks 7-8)\n- Metrics export\n- Structured logging\n- Configuration management\n- Hot-reload support\n\n### Phase 4: Testing & Hardening (Weeks 9-10)\n- Comprehensive testing\n- Performance optimization\n- Security hardening\n- Documentation\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- Router can handle target throughput of 10,000 RPS\n- Backend updates via informers trigger within 1 second\n- Health checks accurately detect unhealthy backends\n- Metrics exported successfully to Prometheus\n- Zero data loss during configuration reloads\n- P99 latency <50ms for healthy requests","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/proposal.md"},"error":"You must read file /home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/proposal.md before overwriting it. Use the Read tool first","time":{"start":1775848603101,"end":1775848603107}}}}
